if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['oph_p2_ocular_anatomy']=[
  {q:"A 22-year-old contact lens wearer presents with severe ocular pain, photophobia, watering, and rapidly progressive corneal ulceration with greenish discharge. Which organism is classically associated with this presentation?",o:["Staphylococcus epidermidis","Corynebacterium diphtheriae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Moraxella lacunata","Streptococcus viridans"],a:2,e:"Pseudomonas keratitis is strongly associated with contact lens wear and is an important ophthalmic emergency because of rapid stromal necrosis and corneal perforation risk.<br><br>Patients typically present with severe pain, mucopurulent discharge, dense stromal infiltrate, and rapidly worsening visual acuity. Prompt fortified topical antibiotics are required.<br><br>Moraxella (D) usually causes indolent marginal ulcers rather than fulminant corneal destruction.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Corneal transparency is maintained primarily by:",o:["Corneal vascularity","Bowman's membrane","Endothelial pump function","Corneal nerves","Descemet membrane thickness"],a:2,e:"The corneal endothelium actively pumps excess fluid out of the stroma, maintaining corneal deturgescence and transparency.<br><br>Endothelial dysfunction results in stromal edema, epithelial bullae, and visual blurring as seen in pseudophakic bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Corneal vascularity (A) would actually reduce transparency.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops corneal abrasion after fingernail trauma. Which corneal layer regenerates rapidly after injury?",o:["Corneal epithelium","Bowman membrane","Descemet membrane","Endothelium","Stroma"],a:0,e:"The corneal epithelium heals rapidly because of active mitosis of basal epithelial cells and migration from limbal stem cells.<br><br>Most uncomplicated abrasions heal within 24,72 hours if secondary infection is prevented and lubrication is maintained.<br><br>Bowman membrane (B) does not regenerate once destroyed and heals with scarring.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive blurring of vision is found to have keratoconus. Which refractive defect is classically associated with this condition?",o:["Hypermetropia","Regular astigmatism","Irregular astigmatism","Aphakia","Presbyopia"],a:2,e:"Keratoconus causes progressive corneal thinning and ectasia leading to irregular astigmatism and visual distortion.<br><br>Scissoring reflex on retinoscopy and Munson sign are classic examination findings in advanced disease.<br><br>Presbyopia (E) is age-related loss of accommodation unrelated to corneal ectasia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Corneal sensation is supplied mainly through the:",o:["Facial nerve","Optic nerve","Ophthalmic division of trigeminal nerve","Oculomotor nerve","Trochlear nerve"],a:2,e:"The ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve supplies corneal sensation primarily through the nasociliary branch.<br><br>Loss of corneal sensation predisposes patients to neurotrophic keratitis, recurrent epithelial defects, and corneal ulceration.<br><br>The facial nerve (A) mediates blinking but not corneal sensory innervation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe pain and watering after welding exposure without protective goggles. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Photokeratitis","Acute glaucoma","Endophthalmitis","Central retinal vein occlusion","Orbital cellulitis"],a:0,e:"Photokeratitis results from ultraviolet-induced epithelial injury and commonly occurs after welding exposure or snow blindness.<br><br>Patients present several hours later with severe pain, photophobia, blepharospasm, and punctate epithelial erosions on fluorescein staining.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (E) presents with fever, proptosis, and ophthalmoplegia rather than superficial epithelial injury.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with herpes simplex keratitis most classically demonstrates which corneal lesion on fluorescein staining?",o:["Ring infiltrate","Dendritic ulcer","Mooren ulcer","Shield ulcer","Hypopyon ulcer"],a:1,e:"Herpes simplex keratitis classically produces branching dendritic ulcers with terminal bulbs that stain with fluorescein.<br><br>Topical steroids without antiviral coverage may worsen viral replication and precipitate corneal perforation.<br><br>Mooren ulcer (C) is a painful peripheral autoimmune ulcerative condition.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The cornea remains avascular primarily to maintain:",o:["Intraocular pressure","Accommodation","Transparency","Aqueous production","Pupillary reflexes"],a:2,e:"Absence of blood vessels minimizes light scattering and is essential for maintaining corneal clarity and optimal visual acuity.<br><br>Corneal neovascularization secondary to chronic hypoxia or inflammation significantly impairs transparency and vision.<br><br>Accommodation (B) depends mainly on lens function rather than corneal vascularity.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe vitamin A deficiency is most likely to develop:",o:["Keratomalacia","Retinal detachment","Papilledema","Uveitis","Vitreous hemorrhage"],a:0,e:"Vitamin A deficiency causes xerophthalmia and corneal liquefactive necrosis known as keratomalacia, particularly in malnourished children.<br><br>This condition may rapidly progress to corneal perforation and irreversible blindness if not treated urgently.<br><br>Papilledema (C) and vitreous hemorrhage (E) are unrelated manifestations.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Corneal graft rejection after penetrating keratoplasty most commonly presents with:",o:["Cherry-red spot","Khodadoust line","Marcus Gunn pupil","Argyll Robertson pupil","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Khodadoust line represents endothelial rejection characterized by a line of inflammatory cells progressing across the donor endothelium.<br><br>Patients may develop redness, photophobia, decreased vision, and corneal edema requiring urgent steroid therapy.<br><br>Marcus Gunn pupil (C) indicates optic nerve dysfunction rather than graft rejection.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A farmer develops severe corneal ulcer after trauma with vegetative matter. Which organism is most likely responsible?",o:["Candida albicans","Aspergillus species","Staphylococcus aureus","Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Haemophilus influenzae"],a:1,e:"Fungal keratitis commonly follows trauma with vegetative matter and is especially prevalent in agricultural workers.<br><br>Aspergillus and Fusarium are important causative organisms producing dry-looking ulcers with feathery margins and satellite lesions.<br><br>Neisseria (D) typically causes rapidly progressive purulent bacterial keratitis rather than fungal ulcers.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with corneal edema sees colored halos around lights. Which mechanism best explains this symptom?",o:["Light diffraction through edematous cornea","Retinal ischemia","Vitreous degeneration","Lens dislocation","Optic nerve compression"],a:0,e:"Corneal edema disrupts normal transparency and causes diffraction of light, producing colored halos around light sources.<br><br>This symptom is commonly encountered in acute angle closure glaucoma and endothelial dysfunction.<br><br>Retinal ischemia (B) does not produce diffraction halos.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which corneal layer is the thickest?",o:["Epithelium","Bowman membrane","Stroma","Descemet membrane","Endothelium"],a:2,e:"The corneal stroma forms nearly 90% of corneal thickness and consists of regularly arranged collagen lamellae.<br><br>This regular arrangement contributes significantly to corneal transparency and refractive power.<br><br>The endothelium (E) is a single-cell layer and much thinner than the stroma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with neuroparalytic keratitis most likely has damage to the:",o:["Facial nerve","Trochlear nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Abducens nerve","Optic nerve"],a:2,e:"Damage to the trigeminal nerve causes loss of corneal sensation leading to neurotrophic or neuroparalytic keratitis.<br><br>Patients may develop painless epithelial defects, stromal ulceration, and secondary infection because protective corneal reflexes are absent.<br><br>Facial nerve palsy mainly predisposes to exposure keratitis rather than sensory denervation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dry eye develops superficial punctate keratitis. Which tear film layer is produced mainly by meibomian glands?",o:["Mucin layer","Aqueous layer","Lipid layer","Stromal layer","Endothelial layer"],a:2,e:"The meibomian glands secrete the lipid component of the tear film, reducing evaporation of tears from the ocular surface.<br><br>Meibomian gland dysfunction predisposes to evaporative dry eye and superficial punctate keratitis.<br><br>The aqueous layer (B) is produced mainly by the lacrimal gland.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute corneal hydrops in keratoconus develops sudden visual deterioration because of rupture in:",o:["Bowman membrane","Corneal epithelium","Descemet membrane","Limbal vessels","Endothelium only"],a:2,e:"Acute corneal hydrops occurs when Descemet membrane ruptures, allowing aqueous humor to enter the corneal stroma rapidly.<br><br>This produces sudden corneal edema, pain, and marked visual loss in advanced keratoconus.<br><br>Bowman membrane rupture (A) does not produce acute stromal hydration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which corneal dystrophy classically shows \"beaten metal\" appearance on slit lamp examination?",o:["Fuchs endothelial dystrophy","Lattice dystrophy","Macular dystrophy","Reis-Bücklers dystrophy","Granular dystrophy"],a:0,e:"Fuchs endothelial dystrophy is characterized by endothelial guttata giving a beaten metal appearance on slit lamp examination.<br><br>Progressive endothelial failure eventually causes stromal edema and bullous keratopathy.<br><br>Lattice dystrophy (B) presents with branching refractile stromal lines instead.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with exposure keratitis secondary to facial nerve palsy primarily develops corneal damage because of inability to:",o:["Produce aqueous humor","Constrict pupil","Close eyelids completely","Accommodate","Move eyeball upward"],a:2,e:"Facial nerve palsy causes lagophthalmos and exposure of the corneal surface, resulting in drying and epithelial breakdown.<br><br>Prompt lubrication and eye protection are essential to prevent corneal ulceration and perforation.<br><br>Accommodation (D) is unrelated to corneal exposure injury.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Acanthamoeba keratitis typically presents with:",o:["Mild painless redness only","Severe pain disproportionate to findings","Sudden retinal hemorrhage","White pupillary reflex","Bilateral papilledema"],a:1,e:"Acanthamoeba keratitis is commonly associated with contact lens wear and produces severe pain often disproportionate to early clinical signs.<br><br>Ring infiltrates may develop later, and delayed diagnosis can lead to significant visual morbidity.<br><br>Leukocoria (D) and papilledema (E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Corneal reflex is mediated by which cranial nerves?",o:["II and III","III and IV","V and VII","VI and VIII","IX and X"],a:2,e:"The afferent limb of the corneal reflex is mediated by the ophthalmic division of trigeminal nerve, while the efferent limb is mediated by the facial nerve.<br><br>Loss of this reflex may indicate lesions involving either trigeminal sensory pathways or facial motor pathways.<br><br>Cranial nerves IX and X (E) are involved mainly in gag reflex pathways.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with recurrent itching, watering, and ropy discharge during spring season. Which conjunctival disorder is most likely?",o:["Vernal keratoconjunctivitis","Bacterial conjunctivitis","Acute anterior uveitis","Hordeolum externum","Blepharitis"],a:0,e:"Vernal keratoconjunctivitis is a chronic allergic conjunctival disease affecting children and young adults, especially in warm climates.<br><br>Giant papillae, intense itching, and ropy mucous discharge are classic features. Corneal involvement may threaten vision in severe disease.<br><br>Bacterial conjunctivitis (B) typically produces purulent rather than ropy mucoid discharge.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Bitot spots are classically associated with:",o:["Vitamin A deficiency","Vitamin C deficiency","Vitamin D deficiency","Vitamin K deficiency","Vitamin B12 deficiency"],a:0,e:"Bitot spots are foamy keratinized conjunctival plaques caused by xerosis secondary to vitamin A deficiency.<br><br>They are important early ophthalmic signs of xerophthalmia and nutritional deficiency in children.<br><br>Vitamin C deficiency (B) is associated mainly with hemorrhagic manifestations rather than conjunctival xerosis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with trachoma develops entropion and trichiasis because of conjunctival:",o:["Fibrosis and scarring","Edema","Chemosis","Acute hyperemia","Papillary hypertrophy"],a:0,e:"Chronic trachoma causes conjunctival fibrosis leading to inward turning of eyelids and lashes that abrade the cornea.<br><br>Corneal scarring from repeated trauma remains a major cause of preventable blindness worldwide.<br><br>Chemosis (C) refers to conjunctival edema rather than cicatricial deformity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops sudden conjunctival hemorrhage after coughing violently. Vision remains normal and pain is absent. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Acute angle closure glaucoma","Subconjunctival hemorrhage","Endophthalmitis","Optic neuritis","Corneal ulcer"],a:1,e:"Subconjunctival hemorrhage results from rupture of small conjunctival vessels and commonly follows coughing, sneezing, or minor trauma.<br><br>The condition appears alarming but is usually benign and self-limiting with preserved vision and absence of pain.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (A) causes severe pain, corneal edema, and visual impairment.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Follicles in the conjunctiva are most characteristically seen in:",o:["Viral conjunctivitis","Acute iridocyclitis","Corneal abrasion","Acute glaucoma","Episcleritis"],a:0,e:"Follicles are small lymphoid aggregates commonly seen in viral conjunctivitis, chlamydial infections, and toxic conjunctivitis.<br><br>Preauricular lymphadenopathy and watery discharge further support viral etiology.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (D) presents with corneal haze and fixed mid-dilated pupil rather than follicles.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with adenoviral conjunctivitis is most likely to have:",o:["Preauricular lymphadenopathy","Purulent discharge","Hypopyon formation","Fixed dilated pupil","Cherry-red spot"],a:0,e:"Adenoviral conjunctivitis commonly presents with watery discharge, follicles, conjunctival congestion, and tender preauricular lymph nodes.<br><br>The condition is highly contagious and often spreads in schools and clinical settings.<br><br>Hypopyon (C) suggests severe corneal ulceration rather than viral conjunctivitis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic conjunctival scarring and Herbert pits most likely suffers from:",o:["Vernal keratoconjunctivitis","Trachoma","Episcleritis","Bacterial conjunctivitis","Keratoconus"],a:1,e:"Herbert pits are limbal depressions resulting from healed trachomatous follicles and are characteristic of chronic trachoma.<br><br>Conjunctival scarring may eventually produce trichiasis, corneal ulceration, and blindness.<br><br>Bacterial conjunctivitis (D) does not cause chronic conjunctival fibrosis and limbal pitting.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with membranous conjunctivitis is at greatest risk of developing:",o:["Symblepharon formation","Retinal detachment","Macular edema","Vitreous hemorrhage","Optic atrophy"],a:0,e:"Membranous conjunctivitis may heal with adhesions between palpebral and bulbar conjunctiva known as symblepharon.<br><br>Chemical injuries and severe membranous infections are important causes of conjunctival cicatrization.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) is unrelated to conjunctival membrane formation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe itching and giant cobblestone papillae on upper tarsal conjunctiva most likely has:",o:["Vernal keratoconjunctivitis","Trachoma","Acute iridocyclitis","Orbital cellulitis","Dacryocystitis"],a:0,e:"Giant cobblestone papillae on the upper tarsal conjunctiva are classic findings in vernal keratoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Corneal shield ulcers may occur in severe disease and threaten visual acuity if untreated.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (D) presents with fever, proptosis, and painful eye movements rather than allergic papillary hypertrophy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops conjunctival xerosis due to severe malnutrition. Which vitamin deficiency is responsible?",o:["Vitamin A deficiency","Vitamin E deficiency","Vitamin K deficiency","Vitamin B6 deficiency","Vitamin D deficiency"],a:0,e:"Vitamin A deficiency causes conjunctival dryness, Bitot spots, corneal xerosis, and keratomalacia collectively termed xerophthalmia.<br><br>Early recognition and supplementation are essential to prevent irreversible blindness in children.<br><br>Vitamin K deficiency (C) mainly affects coagulation pathways rather than ocular surface integrity.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn develops severe purulent conjunctivitis within 48 hours of birth. Which organism is the most likely cause?",o:["Chlamydia trachomatis","Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Staphylococcus epidermidis","Adenovirus","Moraxella lacunata"],a:1,e:"Gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum presents early with profuse purulent discharge and severe conjunctival inflammation.<br><br>Rapid corneal involvement and perforation may occur if urgent systemic and topical antibiotics are not initiated promptly.<br><br>Chlamydial conjunctivitis (A) usually presents later, after 5,14 days.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic unilateral follicular conjunctivitis should raise suspicion for:",o:["Chlamydial conjunctivitis","Chalazion","Acute glaucoma","Retinal detachment","Corneal dystrophy"],a:0,e:"Chronic follicular conjunctivitis, particularly if unilateral and persistent, should prompt evaluation for chlamydial infection.<br><br>Associated preauricular lymphadenopathy and superior corneal pannus may be present.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (C) does not produce chronic follicles.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with allergic conjunctivitis most commonly complains of:",o:["Severe ocular pain","Itching","Sudden blindness","Diplopia","Colored halos"],a:1,e:"Itching is the hallmark symptom of allergic conjunctivitis and helps differentiate it from infective causes.<br><br>Watering, papillary reaction, and bilateral involvement are common associated features.<br><br>Severe ocular pain (A) suggests more serious pathology such as keratitis or glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which conjunctival structure contains accessory lacrimal glands of Wolfring and Krause?",o:["Fornix conjunctiva","Limbal conjunctiva","Corneal epithelium","Tarsal plate","Caruncle only"],a:0,e:"Accessory lacrimal glands located within the conjunctival fornices contribute to basal aqueous tear secretion.<br><br>These glands help maintain ocular surface lubrication and tear film stability.<br><br>The tarsal plate (D) mainly contains meibomian glands rather than accessory lacrimal glands.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Stevens-Johnson syndrome develops severe conjunctival scarring. Which complication may subsequently occur?",o:["Symblepharon","Retinal vein occlusion","Vitreous detachment","Papilledema","Optic neuritis"],a:0,e:"Severe cicatrizing conjunctivitis in Stevens-Johnson syndrome may lead to adhesions between palpebral and bulbar conjunctiva.<br><br>Chronic dry eye, corneal vascularization, and visual loss may follow severe ocular surface disease.<br><br>Papilledema (D) is unrelated to conjunctival cicatrization.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Papillary conjunctival reaction is most characteristically associated with:",o:["Allergic conjunctivitis","Optic atrophy","Retinitis pigmentosa","Retinal artery occlusion","Keratoconus"],a:0,e:"Papillae are vascular conjunctival elevations commonly seen in allergic conjunctivitis and contact lens-related irritation.<br><br>Large cobblestone papillae are particularly characteristic of vernal keratoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Retinal artery occlusion (D) does not produce conjunctival papillary changes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chemical injury to the eye develops blanching of conjunctival vessels. This finding suggests:",o:["Limbal ischemia","Mild injury only","Viral conjunctivitis","Episcleritis","Corneal dystrophy"],a:0,e:"Blanching of conjunctival and limbal vessels indicates severe ocular chemical injury with ischemic damage to limbal stem cells.<br><br>This finding carries poor prognostic significance for corneal epithelial healing.<br><br>Viral conjunctivitis (C) typically causes hyperemia rather than ischemic blanching.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with conjunctival squamous neoplasia most commonly presents as:",o:["Gelatinous limbal mass","Pigmented retinal lesion","White cataract","Vitreous opacity","Papilledema"],a:0,e:"Ocular surface squamous neoplasia commonly appears as a gelatinous or leukoplakic lesion near the limbus.<br><br>Ultraviolet exposure and HPV infection are important risk factors.<br><br>Papilledema (E) affects the optic disc rather than conjunctival tissue.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with subconjunctival hemorrhage should be reassured primarily because the condition usually:",o:["Causes retinal damage","Produces optic atrophy","Resolves spontaneously","Requires emergency surgery","Causes glaucoma"],a:2,e:"Most subconjunctival hemorrhages are harmless and clear spontaneously over one to two weeks without visual consequences.<br><br>Patients should still be evaluated for trauma, hypertension, anticoagulant use, or bleeding disorders when indicated.<br><br>Emergency surgery (D) is not typically required.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The conjunctiva is lined predominantly by:",o:["Keratinized squamous epithelium","Transitional epithelium","Non-keratinized stratified epithelium","Columnar respiratory epithelium only","Cuboidal epithelium only"],a:2,e:"The conjunctiva is lined by non-keratinized stratified epithelium containing goblet cells that contribute mucin to the tear film.<br><br>Loss of goblet cells in cicatrizing diseases leads to tear film instability and ocular surface dryness.<br><br>Keratinization occurs pathologically in severe vitamin A deficiency and ocular surface disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old woman with long-standing rheumatoid arthritis presents with severe boring ocular pain radiating to the temple, photophobia, and violaceous scleral discoloration. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Episcleritis","Scleritis","Viral conjunctivitis","Acute iridocyclitis","Corneal abrasion"],a:1,e:"Scleritis is a painful destructive inflammation involving the deep scleral tissues and is strongly associated with systemic autoimmune disease, especially rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br>Patients typically present with severe boring pain, tenderness, deep congestion, and reduced vision. Necrotizing forms may lead to scleral thinning and perforation.<br><br>Episcleritis (A) is milder, usually painless or minimally painful, and self-limiting. Viral conjunctivitis (C) produces watery discharge and follicles rather than deep scleral tenderness. Corneal abrasion (E) causes superficial foreign body sensation rather than severe radiating pain.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with localized sectoral redness and mild ocular discomfort. The congested vessels blanch after topical phenylephrine instillation. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Scleritis","Endophthalmitis","Episcleritis","Acute glaucoma","Keratitis"],a:2,e:"Episcleritis is a benign superficial inflammatory disorder involving episcleral tissue and vessels.<br><br>Patients usually have mild irritation without significant visual loss or severe pain. Superficial vessels blanch with topical vasoconstrictors such as phenylephrine.<br><br>Scleritis (A) involves deeper vessels that do not blanch and causes severe pain. Acute glaucoma (D) presents with corneal edema, fixed mid-dilated pupil, and markedly raised intraocular pressure. Keratitis (E) usually causes photophobia and corneal staining defects.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Blue sclera is most classically associated with:",o:["Keratoconus","Osteogenesis imperfecta","Retinitis pigmentosa","Cataract","Acute glaucoma"],a:1,e:"Blue sclera occurs because of scleral thinning that permits visualization of underlying uveal pigment through translucent collagen.<br><br>It is classically associated with osteogenesis imperfecta and other connective tissue disorders affecting collagen formation.<br><br>Keratoconus (A) involves corneal thinning rather than scleral thinning. Retinitis pigmentosa (C) primarily affects photoreceptors. Cataract (D) causes lens opacity without scleral discoloration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with necrotizing scleritis is most likely to have associated:",o:["Allergic conjunctivitis","Retinal detachment","Systemic collagen vascular disease","Refractive error","Blepharitis"],a:2,e:"Necrotizing scleritis has a strong association with systemic autoimmune disorders, particularly rheumatoid arthritis and granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br>The condition may lead to scleral melting, perforation, and severe visual morbidity if untreated.<br><br>Allergic conjunctivitis (A) produces itching and papillary reaction rather than scleral necrosis. Refractive error (D) is unrelated to inflammatory scleral destruction. Blepharitis (E) affects eyelid margins rather than deep scleral tissues.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The sclera is composed predominantly of:",o:["Smooth muscle fibers","Elastic cartilage","Irregular collagen bundles","Stratified squamous epithelium","Neural tissue"],a:2,e:"The sclera consists mainly of dense irregular collagen fibers that provide strength and maintain the shape of the eyeball.<br><br>Unlike the cornea, the collagen arrangement is irregular, making the sclera opaque.<br><br>Smooth muscle fibers (A) are not major structural components of sclera. Neural tissue (E) is found in the retina and optic nerve rather than scleral tissue. Stratified squamous epithelium (D) lines the conjunctiva and cornea, not sclera.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with posterior scleritis most commonly presents with:",o:["Painless conjunctival redness","Itching with papillae","Severe ocular pain and decreased vision","Purulent discharge","Gradual leukocoria"],a:2,e:"Posterior scleritis involves inflammation behind the equator of the globe and commonly causes severe deep pain, painful eye movements, and visual impairment.<br><br>Fundus findings may include choroidal folds or exudative retinal detachment. B-scan ultrasonography is often helpful diagnostically.<br><br>Purulent discharge (D) suggests conjunctivitis rather than posterior scleral disease. Itching with papillae (B) favors allergic conjunctivitis. Leukocoria (E) is associated with retinoblastoma or cataract.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly favors scleritis over episcleritis?",o:["Mild irritation","Sectoral redness","Severe boring pain","Watery discharge","Superficial congestion"],a:2,e:"Severe boring ocular pain radiating to adjacent facial structures is the hallmark feature of scleritis.<br><br>Pain often worsens at night and with eye movement because deeper scleral tissues are inflamed.<br><br>Watery discharge (D) commonly occurs in conjunctivitis. Mild irritation (A) and superficial congestion (E) are more typical of episcleritis. Sectoral redness (B) may occur in both conditions and is therefore less discriminative.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Staphyloma formation occurs because of:",o:["Retinal edema","Vitreous liquefaction","Localized scleral thinning with uveal protrusion","Lens degeneration","Corneal endothelial proliferation"],a:2,e:"Staphyloma refers to ectatic protrusion of weakened sclera lined internally by uveal tissue.<br><br>It may occur after inflammation, trauma, high myopia, or uncontrolled glaucoma.<br><br>Retinal edema (A) does not produce scleral ectasia. Lens degeneration (D) affects accommodation and transparency rather than scleral contour. Corneal endothelial proliferation (E) is unrelated to scleral bulging.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diffuse anterior scleritis is most likely to exhibit:",o:["Deep violaceous congestion","Purulent conjunctival discharge","Corneal dendritic ulcer","White pupillary reflex","Preauricular lymphadenopathy"],a:0,e:"Diffuse anterior scleritis produces characteristic deep bluish-red or violaceous scleral congestion due to inflammation of deep vascular plexuses.<br><br>The involved eye is usually tender and painful with possible reduction in vision.<br><br>Purulent discharge (B) suggests bacterial conjunctivitis. Dendritic ulcer (C) indicates herpes simplex keratitis. Leukocoria (D) occurs in cataract or retinoblastoma. Preauricular lymphadenopathy (E) commonly accompanies viral conjunctivitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Progressive scleral thinning without marked inflammation is characteristic of:",o:["Episcleritis","Scleromalacia perforans","Acute glaucoma","Keratoconus","Corneal ulcer"],a:1,e:"Scleromalacia perforans is a severe necrotizing scleral disorder associated with rheumatoid arthritis and characterized by painless progressive scleral thinning.<br><br>Inflammation may be surprisingly minimal despite advanced scleral destruction.<br><br>Episcleritis (A) is benign and non-destructive. Keratoconus (D) causes corneal rather than scleral thinning. Corneal ulceration (E) involves epithelial and stromal tissue rather than sclera.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which scleral layer becomes continuous anteriorly with the corneal stroma?",o:["Lamina fusca","Choroid","Scleral stroma","Episclera","Retina"],a:2,e:"The scleral stroma forms the major fibrous component of the sclera and continues anteriorly with the corneal stroma near the limbus.<br><br>This structural continuity helps maintain integrity of the globe.<br><br>The choroid (B) is vascular and lies internal to sclera. Retina (E) is the neurosensory layer and not continuous with scleral collagen. Episclera (D) is only a superficial connective tissue layer.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful red eye demonstrates marked tenderness over the globe on palpation. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Viral conjunctivitis","Scleritis","Blepharitis","Dry eye syndrome","Chalazion"],a:1,e:"Globe tenderness is an important sign suggesting deeper scleral inflammation rather than superficial conjunctival disease.<br><br>Patients with scleritis often experience severe pain and photophobia with possible reduction in vision.<br><br>Viral conjunctivitis (A) usually causes watery discharge and follicles without scleral tenderness. Chalazion (E) is a localized eyelid lesion rather than a painful globe disorder.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The sclera receives most of its vascular supply from the:",o:["Central retinal artery","Retinal veins","Episcleral vascular plexus","Optic disc circulation","Vitreous vessels"],a:2,e:"The sclera itself is relatively avascular and derives nutrition mainly from episcleral and choroidal vascular networks.<br><br>Inflammation of episcleral vessels contributes to the redness seen clinically in episcleritis and scleritis.<br><br>The central retinal artery (A) supplies the inner retina rather than scleral tissue. Vitreous vessels (E) are absent in the normal adult eye.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is most strongly associated with scleral melting and perforation risk?",o:["Viral conjunctivitis","Subconjunctival hemorrhage","Necrotizing scleritis","Allergic conjunctivitis","Hordeolum"],a:2,e:"Necrotizing scleritis is the most destructive form of scleral inflammation and may result in severe thinning and perforation.<br><br>Urgent systemic immunosuppressive therapy is often required to preserve ocular integrity.<br><br>Subconjunctival hemorrhage (B) is benign and self-limiting. Hordeolum (E) is a localized eyelid gland infection without scleral involvement. Allergic conjunctivitis (D) causes itching and papillary reaction only.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A highly myopic patient develops posterior ectasia of the globe. This condition is termed:",o:["Buphthalmos","Keratomalacia","Posterior staphyloma","Symblepharon","Hyphaema"],a:2,e:"Posterior staphyloma is an outward bulging of weakened posterior sclera commonly associated with pathological myopia.<br><br>It may lead to retinal stretching, macular degeneration, and progressive visual impairment.<br><br>Buphthalmos (A) refers to enlargement of the globe in congenital glaucoma. Hyphaema (E) is blood in the anterior chamber and unrelated to scleral ectasia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe scleral inflammation develops adjacent peripheral corneal thinning. Which condition best describes this association?",o:["Keratomalacia","Corneal dystrophy","Sclerokeratitis","Episcleritis","Pterygium"],a:2,e:"Sclerokeratitis occurs when severe scleral inflammation extends into the peripheral cornea producing stromal thinning and keratitis.<br><br>Visual prognosis worsens significantly because of risk of corneal perforation and scarring.<br><br>Episcleritis (D) is superficial and usually does not involve the cornea. Pterygium (E) is a fibrovascular conjunctival growth rather than inflammatory scleral disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which structure lies immediately internal to the sclera?",o:["Retina","Lens","Choroid","Vitreous","Corneal endothelium"],a:2,e:"The choroid forms the vascular middle coat of the eye and lies directly beneath the sclera.<br><br>Its pigmentation contributes to the bluish appearance observed in conditions involving scleral thinning.<br><br>The retina (A) lies internal to the choroid rather than immediately against the sclera. Lens (B) and vitreous (D) occupy the intraocular cavity.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe autoimmune scleritis is most likely to require:",o:["Artificial tears only","Topical antihistamines only","Systemic immunosuppressive therapy","Cataract extraction","Laser photocoagulation"],a:2,e:"Severe scleritis frequently requires systemic corticosteroids or immunosuppressive agents because the underlying pathology is commonly autoimmune.<br><br>Prompt therapy is necessary to prevent scleral destruction and visual loss.<br><br>Artificial tears (A) may relieve irritation but cannot control necrotizing inflammation. Topical antihistamines (B) are useful in allergic conjunctivitis rather than scleral autoimmune disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Episcleritis differs from scleritis because episcleritis usually:",o:["Causes perforation","Is benign and self-limiting","Produces scleral necrosis","Causes severe visual loss","Requires immunosuppressants routinely"],a:1,e:"Episcleritis is typically a mild inflammatory condition with excellent prognosis and spontaneous resolution.<br><br>Visual acuity is usually preserved and complications are uncommon.<br><br>Scleritis may cause scleral necrosis (C), severe pain, and visual loss (D). Routine systemic immunosuppression (E) is generally unnecessary in simple episcleritis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The sclera performs all of the following functions EXCEPT:",o:["Maintaining globe shape","Protecting intraocular structures","Providing extraocular muscle attachment","Transmitting visual impulses","Supporting intraocular pressure"],a:3,e:"The sclera forms the tough outer fibrous coat of the eye, maintaining ocular shape and protecting intraocular contents.<br><br>It also provides attachment for extraocular muscles and helps withstand intraocular pressure.<br><br>Transmission of visual impulses is performed by the retina and optic nerve, not the sclera. Extraocular muscle attachment (C) is an important anatomical function of scleral tissue.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old hypertensive patient presents with sudden painless loss of vision. Fundus examination shows extensive retinal hemorrhages, dilated tortuous veins, cotton wool spots, and optic disc edema producing a \"blood and thunder\" appearance. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Central retinal vein occlusion","Retinal detachment","Optic neuritis","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Central retinal vein occlusion (CRVO) is strongly associated with hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and glaucoma. The ischemic type carries high risk of neovascular glaucoma and severe visual loss.<br><br>Fundus findings include widespread flame-shaped and blot hemorrhages, dilated tortuous veins, disc edema, and cotton wool spots. Fluorescein angiography helps differentiate ischemic from non-ischemic CRVO.<br><br>Central retinal artery occlusion (A) produces pale retina with cherry-red spot rather than diffuse hemorrhages. Papilledema (E) is usually bilateral and related to raised intracranial pressure. Retinal detachment (C) presents with flashes and floaters rather than venous congestion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with sudden profound painless monocular blindness. Fundoscopy reveals retinal whitening with a cherry-red spot at the macula. Which artery is occluded?",o:["Posterior ciliary artery","Central retinal artery","Lacrimal artery","Supraorbital artery","Angular artery"],a:1,e:"Central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO) is an ophthalmic emergency commonly caused by emboli from carotid or cardiac sources. Immediate measures include ocular massage, acetazolamide, and reduction of intraocular pressure.<br><br>The retina becomes pale because of ischemia, while the fovea appears cherry-red due to intact choroidal circulation beneath the thin foveal retina.<br><br>Posterior ciliary artery occlusion (A) mainly affects choroid and optic nerve head. Retinal vein occlusion would show hemorrhages instead of retinal pallor.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Night blindness is the earliest symptom of:",o:["Diabetic retinopathy","Central serous retinopathy","Retinitis pigmentosa","Macular degeneration","Optic atrophy"],a:2,e:"Retinitis pigmentosa is an inherited retinal dystrophy characterized initially by rod photoreceptor degeneration, producing nyctalopia. Peripheral visual field constriction follows later.<br><br>Classic fundus findings include bone-spicule pigmentation, attenuated retinal vessels, and waxy optic disc pallor.<br><br>Macular degeneration (D) primarily affects central vision. Diabetic retinopathy (A) causes vascular retinal changes rather than early night blindness. Optic atrophy (E) produces reduced visual acuity and color vision defects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient develops neovascularization at the optic disc and elsewhere in the retina. This finding indicates:",o:["Mild non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy","Proliferative diabetic retinopathy","Hypertensive retinopathy grade 1","Retinitis pigmentosa","Central retinal artery occlusion"],a:1,e:"Retinal ischemia stimulates VEGF release, causing fragile neovascularization characteristic of proliferative diabetic retinopathy (PDR).<br><br>Complications include vitreous hemorrhage and tractional retinal detachment. Pan-retinal photocoagulation remains the standard sight-saving treatment.<br><br>Non-proliferative diabetic retinopathy (A) shows microaneurysms and exudates without neovascularization. CRAO (E) produces acute ischemic whitening rather than proliferative vascular changes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient complains of flashes of light, floaters, and a curtain descending over vision. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Cataract","Acute glaucoma","Retinal detachment","Corneal ulcer","Optic neuritis"],a:2,e:"Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment typically presents with photopsia, floaters, and progressive shadow-like visual field loss.<br><br>Retinal tears permit vitreous fluid to enter the subretinal space, separating the neurosensory retina from retinal pigment epithelium. Early surgery improves prognosis before macular detachment occurs.<br><br>Acute glaucoma (B) presents with pain and halos. Cataract (A) causes gradual painless blurring without flashes or curtain-like defects. Optic neuritis (E) produces painful visual loss and color desaturation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The earliest retinal finding in hypertensive retinopathy is usually:",o:["Cotton wool spots","Hard exudates","Papilledema","Arteriolar narrowing","Vitreous hemorrhage"],a:3,e:"Generalized arteriolar narrowing is an early vascular response to hypertension caused by vasospasm and vascular wall thickening.<br><br>Progressive disease later produces hemorrhages, cotton wool spots, hard exudates, and papilledema in malignant hypertension.<br><br>Papilledema (C) indicates severe malignant hypertension rather than early disease. Vitreous hemorrhage (E) is more characteristic of proliferative diabetic retinopathy.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with proliferative diabetic retinopathy suddenly develops severe visual loss due to vitreous hemorrhage. The hemorrhage most likely arises from:",o:["Retinal pigment epithelium","Macular edema","Choroidal melanoma","Fragile neovascular vessels","Corneal neovascularization"],a:3,e:"New vessels formed in proliferative diabetic retinopathy lack normal vascular integrity and bleed easily into the vitreous cavity.<br><br>Patients often describe sudden floaters, cobwebs, or dark visual haze. Recurrent hemorrhage may require vitrectomy.<br><br>Macular edema (B) causes gradual central blurring rather than acute vitreous bleeding. Corneal neovascularization (E) does not cause vitreous hemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal layer contains the nuclei of rods and cones?",o:["Ganglion cell layer","Nerve fiber layer","Inner plexiform layer","Outer nuclear layer","Internal limiting membrane"],a:3,e:"The outer nuclear layer contains the cell bodies of photoreceptors responsible for conversion of light into neural signals.<br><br>Degeneration of rods predominates in retinitis pigmentosa, while cone dysfunction causes impaired central and color vision.<br><br>Ganglion cell layer (A) contains neurons whose axons form the optic nerve. Nerve fiber layer (B) carries retinal nerve fibers toward the optic disc.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young stressed executive presents with metamorphopsia and blurred central vision. Fundus reveals localized serous detachment at the macula. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Central serous chorioretinopathy","Retinal vein occlusion","Retinitis pigmentosa","Endophthalmitis","Papilledema"],a:0,e:"Central serous chorioretinopathy (CSCR) commonly affects young stressed males and is associated with corticosteroid use.<br><br>Leakage from the choroid causes serous detachment of the neurosensory retina at the macula producing metamorphopsia and micropsia.<br><br>Retinal vein occlusion (B) causes hemorrhages and venous tortuosity. Papilledema (E) causes optic disc swelling rather than isolated serous macular elevation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Papilledema most commonly results from:",o:["Raised intracranial pressure","Corneal edema","Retinal detachment","Cataract","Central retinal artery occlusion"],a:0,e:"Papilledema refers to bilateral optic disc swelling caused by raised intracranial pressure. Visual acuity may initially remain normal despite marked disc edema.<br><br>Common symptoms include headache, vomiting, and transient visual obscurations. Chronic papilledema eventually causes secondary optic atrophy.<br><br>CRAO (E) causes retinal pallor and sudden blindness rather than bilateral disc edema. Corneal edema (B) affects the anterior segment only.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with age-related macular degeneration develops sudden deterioration of central vision due to choroidal neovascularization. Which type of AMD is most likely present?",o:["Dry AMD","Wet AMD","Retinitis pigmentosa","Hypertensive retinopathy","Branch retinal vein occlusion"],a:1,e:"Wet age-related macular degeneration is characterized by choroidal neovascular membrane formation beneath the retina causing leakage and hemorrhage.<br><br>Anti-VEGF intravitreal injections are the current mainstay of treatment and may stabilize or improve vision.<br><br>Dry AMD (A) causes drusen and geographic atrophy with slower visual decline. Retinitis pigmentosa (C) primarily affects peripheral retina.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with branch retinal vein occlusion most commonly presents with:",o:["Sectoral retinal hemorrhages","Total retinal whitening","Cherry-red spot","Bilateral papilledema","Bone-spicule pigmentation"],a:0,e:"Branch retinal vein occlusion produces hemorrhages, cotton wool spots, and venous dilation confined to the affected venous drainage territory.<br><br>Hypertension is a major risk factor. Macular edema is the commonest cause of visual impairment.<br><br>CRAO (B and C) causes diffuse retinal pallor with cherry-red spot. Bone-spicule pigmentation (E) occurs in retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal condition is most strongly associated with high myopia?",o:["Rhegmatogenous retinal detachment","Papilledema","Central retinal artery occlusion","Optic neuritis","Episcleritis"],a:0,e:"High myopia predisposes to lattice degeneration and retinal tears that may progress to rhegmatogenous retinal detachment.<br><br>Patients should be educated about warning symptoms such as flashes, floaters, and field defects.<br><br>Papilledema (B) results from raised intracranial pressure. Optic neuritis (D) is inflammatory demyelinating optic nerve disease. Episcleritis (E) affects the sclera superficially.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Hard exudates seen in diabetic retinopathy represent:",o:["Lipid deposits from leaky capillaries","Retinal hemorrhages","Fungal infiltrates","Optic nerve edema","Fibrous retinal scars"],a:0,e:"Hard exudates are yellow lipid-rich deposits resulting from chronic leakage through incompetent retinal capillaries.<br><br>Circinate rings of hard exudates around microaneurysms are highly suggestive of diabetic maculopathy.<br><br>Retinal hemorrhages (B) appear red rather than yellow. Optic nerve edema (D) causes blurred disc margins instead of retinal lipid deposition.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal detachment undergoes scleral buckling surgery. The main purpose of scleral buckle is to:",o:["Reduce aqueous production","Improve corneal transparency","Destroy retinal vessels","Close retinal breaks externally","Lower intracranial pressure"],a:3,e:"Scleral buckling indents the scleral wall toward the retinal tear, reducing vitreoretinal traction and facilitating retinal reattachment.<br><br>Cryotherapy or laser photocoagulation is usually added to seal retinal breaks permanently.<br><br>Aqueous suppression (A) is used in glaucoma management. Corneal transparency (B) is unrelated to retinal detachment surgery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Cotton wool spots in hypertensive or diabetic retinopathy represent:",o:["Lipid exudation","Vitreous opacities","Choroidal tumors","Retinal nerve fiber layer infarcts","Retinal tears"],a:3,e:"Cotton wool spots are microinfarctions of the retinal nerve fiber layer caused by occlusion of precapillary arterioles.<br><br>They appear as fluffy white lesions and indicate significant retinal ischemia.<br><br>Hard exudates (A) are lipid deposits, while retinal tears (E) predispose to retinal detachment rather than ischemic whitening.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sudden painless central visual loss and distorted images is found to have a macular hole. Which symptom is classically present?",o:["Metamorphopsia","Colored halos","Severe photophobia","Purulent discharge","Diplopia"],a:0,e:"Macular holes produce distortion and reduction of central vision because of disruption of the foveal architecture.<br><br>Optical coherence tomography (OCT) is the gold standard investigation for diagnosis and surgical planning.<br><br>Colored halos (B) are associated with corneal edema. Purulent discharge (D) suggests infective conjunctivitis rather than macular pathology. Diplopia (E) is usually extraocular muscle related.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The fovea centralis contains predominantly:",o:["Rod cells","Ganglion cells only","Bipolar cells only","Cone cells","Retinal vessels"],a:3,e:"The fovea is specialized for high-acuity and color vision because of dense concentration of cone photoreceptors.<br><br>Retinal vessels are absent at the foveal center to minimize light scattering and maximize visual precision.<br><br>Rod cells (A) predominate in peripheral retina and are responsible for dim-light vision. Ganglion cells (B) are displaced away from the foveal pit.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with diabetic macular edema is most likely to complain of:",o:["Peripheral field constriction","Night blindness","Severe ocular pain","Central visual blurring","Diplopia"],a:3,e:"Diabetic macular edema is the leading cause of visual impairment in diabetic retinopathy because fluid accumulation affects central retinal function.<br><br>Optical coherence tomography is highly useful for detecting and monitoring macular edema. Anti-VEGF therapy is commonly employed.<br><br>Peripheral field constriction (A) is typical of retinitis pigmentosa. Severe pain (C) is uncommon in retinal vascular disease. Night blindness (B) suggests rod dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with longstanding papilledema eventually develops optic disc pallor and visual decline. This stage is termed:",o:["Optic neuritis","Macular degeneration","Retinal vasculitis","Secondary optic atrophy","Retinal dystrophy"],a:3,e:"Persistent papilledema damages optic nerve fibers leading to secondary optic atrophy characterized by pale swollen discs and progressive visual loss.<br><br>Early identification and treatment of raised intracranial pressure are essential to prevent irreversible blindness.<br><br>Optic neuritis (A) causes painful visual loss with demyelinating inflammation. Retinal dystrophy (E) primarily affects photoreceptors rather than optic nerve fibers.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old diabetic patient complains of gradually progressive painless diminution of vision with increasing glare while driving at night. Examination reveals nuclear sclerosis. Which symptom is classically associated with nuclear cataract?",o:["Sudden painful visual loss","Colored halos due to corneal edema","Metamorphopsia","Second sight phenomenon","Monocular diplopia only in children"],a:3,e:"Nuclear cataract commonly causes index myopia, temporarily improving near vision in elderly patients, known as \"second sight.\" Progressive lens sclerosis later causes worsening visual acuity and glare.<br><br>Night-driving difficulty and reduced contrast sensitivity are high-yield clinical clues. Nuclear cataract is the commonest senile cataract subtype in FCPS recalls.<br><br>Colored halos (B) are more typical of acute glaucoma. Metamorphopsia (C) suggests macular disease. Sudden painful loss (A) is inconsistent with cataract progression.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops painful red eye with corneal edema and shallow anterior chamber due to swollen mature cataract. Which type of glaucoma is most likely?",o:["Primary open-angle glaucoma","Phacomorphic glaucoma","Neovascular glaucoma","Congenital glaucoma","Pigmentary glaucoma"],a:1,e:"Phacomorphic glaucoma occurs when an intumescent mature lens pushes the iris anteriorly, causing secondary angle closure and acute rise of intraocular pressure.<br><br>Patients present with pain, redness, halos, corneal edema, and shallow anterior chamber. Definitive treatment is cataract extraction after pressure control.<br><br>Primary open-angle glaucoma (A) is chronic and painless. Neovascular glaucoma (C) is associated with retinal ischemia and rubeosis iridis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with leukocoria, nystagmus, and bilateral lens opacity since birth. Which condition is most likely?",o:["Congenital cataract","Retinoblastoma","Retinal detachment","Optic neuritis","Retinitis pigmentosa"],a:0,e:"Congenital cataract is an important cause of preventable childhood blindness and requires early surgical intervention to prevent deprivation amblyopia.<br><br>Dense bilateral cataracts presenting with leukocoria and nystagmus indicate severe visual deprivation. TORCH infections are important etiological associations.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) also causes leukocoria but is commonly associated with retinal mass rather than isolated lens opacity. Retinitis pigmentosa (E) causes night blindness instead of leukocoria.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The lens receives its nutrition primarily from:",o:["Retinal vessels","Vitreous vessels","Choroidal circulation","Aqueous humor","Central retinal artery"],a:3,e:"The crystalline lens is avascular and depends mainly on aqueous humor for metabolic exchange and nutrition.<br><br>Any disturbance in aqueous composition may contribute to lens opacification. This avascularity is important for lens transparency.<br><br>Retinal vessels (A) and central retinal artery (E) supply retinal tissue, not the lens. Vitreous vessels (B) are absent in normal adults.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops sudden painless monocular diplopia that disappears when the affected eye is closed. Which lens pathology is most likely?",o:["Retinal detachment","Corneal abrasion","Optic neuritis","Early cataract","Papilledema"],a:3,e:"Monocular diplopia is a classic early symptom of cataract due to irregular refraction through partially opaque lens fibers.<br><br>Patients may also complain of glare, reduced contrast sensitivity, and ghost images.<br><br>Optic neuritis (C) causes painful visual loss and color desaturation. Retinal detachment (A) causes flashes and curtain-like field loss rather than monocular diplopia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops retained lens matter after cataract surgery causing severe postoperative inflammation and elevated intraocular pressure. Which complication is most likely?",o:["Phacoanaphylactic uveitis","Episcleritis","Retinitis pigmentosa","Central retinal artery occlusion","Vernal conjunctivitis"],a:0,e:"Lens proteins are normally sequestered from the immune system. Exposure after trauma or surgery may trigger severe granulomatous inflammation called phacoanaphylactic uveitis.<br><br>Patients may develop pain, redness, hypopyon, and secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Episcleritis (B) is superficial benign inflammation. Vernal conjunctivitis (E) is allergic and unrelated to lens proteins.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which lens fibers are formed throughout life?",o:["Primary lens fibers only","Corneal stromal fibers","Zonular fibers","Secondary lens fibers","Hyaloid fibers"],a:3,e:"Secondary lens fibers continue to develop throughout life from lens epithelial cells near the equator, contributing to progressive lens enlargement.<br><br>Compaction of older fibers centrally produces the adult lens nucleus. Age-related sclerosis contributes to senile cataract formation.<br><br>Primary lens fibers (A) form the embryonic nucleus only. Zonular fibers (C) suspend the lens but are not lens fibers themselves.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hypermature cataract develops leakage of lens proteins through the capsule causing secondary open-angle glaucoma. Which condition is this?",o:["Phacolytic glaucoma","Phacomorphic glaucoma","Pigmentary glaucoma","Angle recession glaucoma","Congenital glaucoma"],a:0,e:"Phacolytic glaucoma occurs in hypermature cataracts when leaked high-molecular-weight lens proteins obstruct the trabecular meshwork.<br><br>Patients present with painful red eye, elevated intraocular pressure, and a mature cataract.<br><br>Phacomorphic glaucoma (B) is caused by lens swelling with angle closure rather than protein leakage. Pigmentary glaucoma (C) results from pigment dispersion syndrome.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Marfan syndrome is most likely to develop:",o:["Inferonasal lens subluxation","Superotemporal lens subluxation","Mature cataract at birth","Posterior polar cataract only","Corneal hydrops"],a:1,e:"Marfan syndrome classically causes ectopia lentis due to zonular weakness, with the lens displaced upward and temporally.<br><br>Patients may also have high myopia and increased risk of retinal detachment.<br><br>Inferonasal displacement (A) is more characteristic of homocystinuria. Corneal hydrops (E) is associated with keratoconus rather than lens instability.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which structure suspends the lens in position?",o:["Canal of Schlemm","Ciliary nerves","Hyaloid artery","Zonular fibers","Trabecular meshwork"],a:3,e:"The lens is suspended by zonular fibers extending from the ciliary body to the lens capsule.<br><br>Contraction of the ciliary muscle relaxes zonules during accommodation, allowing the lens to become more convex.<br><br>Canal of Schlemm (A) and trabecular meshwork (E) are involved in aqueous drainage rather than lens support.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient complains of glare and difficulty driving at night despite relatively preserved daytime vision. Which cataract type most commonly produces this symptom?",o:["Nuclear cataract","Sutural cataract","Lamellar cataract","Posterior subcapsular cataract","Polar cataract"],a:3,e:"Posterior subcapsular cataracts disproportionately affect near vision and produce disabling glare, especially in bright light and nighttime driving.<br><br>Steroid use, diabetes, and radiation exposure are important risk factors.<br><br>Nuclear cataract (A) commonly produces myopic shift and gradual visual decline rather than marked glare early. Lamellar cataract (C) is congenital.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The embryological origin of the lens is:",o:["Neural crest","Surface ectoderm","Mesoderm","Neuroectoderm","Endoderm"],a:1,e:"The lens develops from surface ectoderm through formation of the lens placode and lens vesicle.<br><br>This is a repeatedly tested embryology fact in FCPS and JCAT recalls, often integrated with congenital cataract questions.<br><br>Neuroectoderm (D) forms the retina and optic nerve rather than the lens. Neural crest (A) contributes to corneal endothelium and stroma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops posterior capsular opacification months after successful cataract surgery. Which treatment is preferred?",o:["Penetrating keratoplasty","Vitrectomy","Trabeculectomy","Nd:YAG laser capsulotomy","Cyclocryotherapy"],a:3,e:"Posterior capsular opacification is the commonest late complication of cataract surgery and results from proliferation of residual lens epithelial cells.<br><br>Nd:YAG laser posterior capsulotomy restores the visual axis quickly and painlessly.<br><br>Trabeculectomy (C) is performed for glaucoma. Penetrating keratoplasty (A) is indicated for corneal opacity rather than posterior capsule fibrosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Accommodation occurs because of:",o:["Increased zonular tension","Corneal curvature changes","Lens flattening","Relaxation of zonular fibers","Iris contraction only"],a:3,e:"During accommodation, ciliary muscle contraction relaxes zonular fibers, allowing the elastic lens to become more convex for near focus.<br><br>Loss of lens elasticity with age leads to presbyopia.<br><br>Increased zonular tension (A) actually flattens the lens for distance vision. Corneal curvature (B) does not significantly change during accommodation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops cataract after blunt trauma. Which type is classically described?",o:["Rosette cataract","Snowflake cataract","Blue-dot cataract","Sutural cataract","Coronary cataract"],a:0,e:"Blunt ocular trauma may produce characteristic rosette-shaped posterior cortical opacities due to lens fiber disruption.<br><br>Traumatic cataracts may appear immediately or develop gradually after injury.<br><br>Snowflake cataract (B) is associated with uncontrolled diabetes. Sutural cataract (D) is congenital and usually visually insignificant.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient develops bilateral cortical opacities resembling snowflakes. Which cataract type is this?",o:["Nuclear cataract","Traumatic cataract","Snowflake cataract","Posterior polar cataract","Morgagnian cataract"],a:2,e:"Snowflake cataract is a rapidly developing cataract seen in uncontrolled diabetes mellitus due to osmotic lens swelling from sorbitol accumulation.<br><br>It is more common in younger diabetic patients.<br><br>Morgagnian cataract (E) refers to liquefaction of the cortex in hypermature cataract. Posterior polar cataract (D) is congenital.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which cataract is most strongly associated with prolonged corticosteroid use?",o:["Nuclear cataract","Coronary cataract","Lamellar cataract","Posterior subcapsular cataract","Traumatic cataract"],a:3,e:"Long-term corticosteroid therapy is a classic cause of posterior subcapsular cataract. Diabetes and radiation are additional associations.<br><br>Patients complain disproportionately of glare and near vision difficulty despite relatively preserved distance acuity initially.<br><br>Lamellar cataract (C) is congenital. Traumatic cataract (E) follows ocular injury rather than steroid exposure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient becomes aphakic after cataract extraction without intraocular lens implantation. Which refractive change is expected?",o:["High myopia","Presbyopia only","Astigmatism only","High hypermetropia","Emmetropia"],a:3,e:"Removal of the crystalline lens eliminates a major refractive component of the eye, resulting in marked hypermetropia in aphakia.<br><br>Patients also lose accommodation completely.<br><br>High myopia (A) is opposite to the expected refractive outcome. Presbyopia (B) refers to age-related accommodative decline, whereas aphakia causes total accommodative loss.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hypermature cataract demonstrates sinking of the nucleus within liquefied cortex. Which cataract type is this?",o:["Posterior polar cataract","Nuclear cataract","Lamellar cataract","Morgagnian cataract","Rosette cataract"],a:3,e:"Morgagnian cataract is a hypermature cataract in which cortical liquefaction allows the dense nucleus to sink inferiorly.<br><br>These lenses may leak proteins causing phacolytic glaucoma.<br><br>Rosette cataract (E) follows blunt trauma. Posterior polar cataract (A) is congenital and located at the posterior capsule.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The lens capsule is thickest at the:",o:["Posterior pole","Posterior cortex","Equator","Anterior pole","Nucleus"],a:3,e:"The anterior lens capsule is thicker because it overlies the anterior lens epithelium, which remains metabolically active throughout life.<br><br>Posterior capsule rupture is an important complication during cataract surgery because the posterior capsule is thinner and more fragile.<br><br>The nucleus (E) is composed of compacted lens fibers and has no capsule. Posterior cortex (B) lies internal to the capsule rather than forming it.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old patient presents with painful red eye, photophobia, circumcorneal congestion, and small irregular pupil. Slit lamp examination shows cells and flare in the anterior chamber. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Acute conjunctivitis","Acute anterior uveitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Episcleritis","Corneal abrasion"],a:1,e:"Acute anterior uveitis is one of the most repeatedly recalled FCPS ophthalmology topics. Classic findings are pain, photophobia, circumcorneal congestion, cells, flare, and posterior synechiae.<br><br>Patients often have consensual photophobia and ciliary tenderness. HLA-B27,associated diseases are important systemic associations. Cycloplegics and topical steroids are standard therapy after excluding infective causes.<br><br>Conjunctivitis (A) produces discharge and diffuse congestion without cells and flare. Acute glaucoma (C) causes mid-dilated pupil and markedly elevated intraocular pressure. Episcleritis (D) is usually painless.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The major arterial circle of the iris is formed primarily by branches of the:",o:["Central retinal artery","Long posterior ciliary arteries","Ophthalmic veins","Lacrimal artery","Supraorbital artery"],a:1,e:"The major arterial circle of the iris is formed by anastomosis between long posterior ciliary arteries and anterior ciliary arteries within the ciliary body.<br><br>This vascular supply is clinically important in anterior uveitis and during intraocular surgery. Disruption may contribute to ischemia and inflammation.<br><br>Central retinal artery (A) mainly supplies the inner retina. Ophthalmic veins (C) are venous drainage structures rather than arterial contributors.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent anterior uveitis develops irregular fixed pupil due to adhesions between iris and lens. What is this complication called?",o:["Peripheral anterior synechiae","Hypopyon","Ectopia lentis","Posterior synechiae","Rubeosis iridis"],a:3,e:"Posterior synechiae are adhesions between the posterior iris surface and anterior lens capsule caused by fibrinous inflammation in anterior uveitis.<br><br>If extensive, they may cause seclusio pupillae and secondary angle-closure glaucoma. Mydriatic cycloplegics are used early to prevent synechiae formation.<br><br>Peripheral anterior synechiae (A) involve adhesion between iris and trabecular meshwork. Rubeosis iridis (E) refers to iris neovascularization.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with ankylosing spondylitis presents with recurrent unilateral painful red eye and photophobia. Which ocular condition is most strongly associated?",o:["Retinitis pigmentosa","Acute anterior uveitis","Optic atrophy","Central retinal vein occlusion","Retinal detachment"],a:1,e:"HLA-B27,associated seronegative spondyloarthropathies, especially ankylosing spondylitis, are strongly associated with recurrent acute anterior uveitis.<br><br>These attacks are often unilateral, recurrent, and painful with marked photophobia and ciliary congestion.<br><br>Retinal detachment (E) presents with flashes and floaters. Central retinal vein occlusion (D) is vascular and usually occurs in older patients with systemic vascular disease.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The ciliary body performs all of the following functions EXCEPT:",o:["Aqueous humor production","Accommodation","Blood-retinal barrier formation","Lens zonule attachment","Uveoscleral outflow contribution"],a:2,e:"The ciliary body produces aqueous humor through the ciliary epithelium and contributes to accommodation through ciliary muscle contraction.<br><br>It also serves as attachment for zonular fibers and participates in uveoscleral outflow pathways.<br><br>The blood-retinal barrier (C) is mainly formed by retinal pigment epithelium and retinal vascular endothelium rather than the ciliary body.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe anterior uveitis develops layering of white inflammatory cells in the anterior chamber. What is this finding called?",o:["Hyphaema","Vitritis","Pseudohypopyon","Hypopyon","Keratic precipitates"],a:3,e:"Hypopyon is accumulation of inflammatory leukocytes in the inferior anterior chamber and may occur in severe uveitis or corneal ulceration.<br><br>Behçet disease is a classic systemic association repeatedly tested in FCPS recalls.<br><br>Hyphaema (A) refers to blood in the anterior chamber. Keratic precipitates (E) are inflammatory deposits on the corneal endothelium rather than layered anterior chamber pus.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic granulomatous uveitis is most likely to show which slit lamp finding?",o:["Fine keratic precipitates","Dendritic ulcer","Corneal guttata","Mutton-fat keratic precipitates","Band keratopathy only"],a:3,e:"Granulomatous uveitis classically produces large greasy \"mutton-fat\" keratic precipitates composed of macrophages and epithelioid cells.<br><br>Tuberculosis, sarcoidosis, and sympathetic ophthalmia are important causes.<br><br>Fine keratic precipitates (A) are more typical of nongranulomatous uveitis. Dendritic ulcers (B) indicate herpes simplex keratitis rather than uveal inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Accommodation occurs primarily due to contraction of the:",o:["Iris sphincter","Orbicularis oculi","Superior rectus","Ciliary muscle","Dilator pupillae"],a:3,e:"Contraction of the ciliary muscle relaxes zonular tension, allowing the lens to become more convex for near vision.<br><br>Loss of lens elasticity with aging causes presbyopia despite intact ciliary muscle function.<br><br>Iris sphincter (A) constricts the pupil but does not directly alter lens curvature. Dilator pupillae (E) controls pupillary dilation.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt ocular trauma develops painful photophobia and blood in the anterior chamber. Which uveal structure is most likely injured?",o:["Choroid only","Optic disc","Retina only","Iris and ciliary body","Macula"],a:3,e:"Blunt trauma commonly damages iris and ciliary body vessels producing traumatic hyphaema.<br><br>Patients require monitoring for secondary glaucoma and rebleeding.<br><br>Macular injury (E) causes visual distortion but not anterior chamber bleeding. Choroidal rupture (A) affects the posterior segment rather than producing hyphaema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The choroid is primarily responsible for:",o:["Accommodation","Nourishing outer retina","Aqueous drainage","Tear production","Lens suspension"],a:1,e:"The choroid is a highly vascular layer supplying oxygen and nutrients to the retinal pigment epithelium and photoreceptors.<br><br>Its rich blood flow explains rapid hematogenous spread of metastatic tumors to the choroid.<br><br>Accommodation (A) is mediated by ciliary muscle. Lens suspension (E) is performed by zonules attached to the ciliary body.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with anterior uveitis develops elevated intraocular pressure because inflammatory cells obstruct the:",o:["Canal of Petit","Vitreous cavity","Hyaloid canal","Trabecular meshwork","Suprachoroidal space"],a:3,e:"Inflammatory cells and proteins may block trabecular outflow in uveitis, producing secondary inflammatory glaucoma.<br><br>Steroid therapy may also contribute to raised intraocular pressure during treatment.<br><br>Suprachoroidal space (E) is involved in uveoscleral pathways rather than primary aqueous drainage obstruction. Vitreous cavity (B) does not regulate intraocular pressure.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops heterochromia, cataract, and chronic low-grade uveitis without posterior synechiae. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Behçet disease","Sympathetic ophthalmia","Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada syndrome","Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma"],a:3,e:"Fuchs heterochromic iridocyclitis is a chronic unilateral anterior uveitis characterized by heterochromia, cataract, diffuse stellate keratic precipitates, and secondary glaucoma.<br><br>Posterior synechiae are characteristically absent despite chronic inflammation.<br><br>Behçet disease (A) causes recurrent hypopyon uveitis. Sympathetic ophthalmia (B) is bilateral granulomatous panuveitis following trauma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral granulomatous panuveitis develops symptoms after penetrating trauma to one eye. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Retinitis pigmentosa","Sympathetic ophthalmia","Central serous retinopathy","Optic neuritis","Episcleritis"],a:1,e:"Sympathetic ophthalmia is a bilateral granulomatous autoimmune uveitis occurring after penetrating injury or surgery involving uveal tissue exposure.<br><br>The uninjured eye becomes inflamed because of autoimmune sensitization to ocular antigens.<br><br>Optic neuritis (D) causes painful visual loss without bilateral granulomatous panuveitis. Episcleritis (E) is superficial and non-destructive.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The pigment epithelium of the iris is embryologically derived from:",o:["Surface ectoderm","Neural crest","Neuroectoderm","Mesoderm","Endoderm"],a:2,e:"The posterior pigmented iris epithelium develops from neuroectoderm, similar to retinal pigment epithelium.<br><br>Embryological derivations are repeatedly integrated into FCPS anatomy questions.<br><br>Surface ectoderm (A) forms the lens. Neural crest (B) contributes to corneal stroma and endothelium rather than pigmented iris epithelium.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic anterior uveitis develops a white horizontal opacity in the superficial cornea due to calcium deposition. What is this condition called?",o:["Arcus senilis","Keratomalacia","Corneal guttata","Band keratopathy","Kayser-Fleischer ring"],a:3,e:"Band keratopathy results from calcium deposition in Bowman layer and superficial cornea, commonly associated with chronic uveitis and hypercalcemia.<br><br>The opacity typically begins in the interpalpebral zone.<br><br>Arcus senilis (A) is peripheral lipid deposition. Kayser-Fleischer ring (E) is copper deposition in Descemet membrane seen in Wilson disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful photophobia has small irregular pupil and perilimbal congestion. Which immediate medication is most useful to prevent posterior synechiae?",o:["Pilocarpine","Acetazolamide","Timolol","Cycloplegic agent","Artificial tears"],a:3,e:"Cycloplegics relieve ciliary spasm pain and prevent posterior synechiae formation by keeping the pupil dilated in anterior uveitis.<br><br>Atropine and homatropine are commonly used.<br><br>Pilocarpine (A) causes miosis and would worsen synechiae formation. Artificial tears (E) do not address intraocular inflammation. Timolol (C) only lowers intraocular pressure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which structure forms the anterior part of the uveal tract?",o:["Retina","Lens","Cornea","Iris","Sclera"],a:3,e:"The uveal tract consists of iris, ciliary body, and choroid. The iris forms the anterior visible component of the uvea.<br><br>Its muscles regulate pupillary size and light entry.<br><br>The retina (A) is neural tissue rather than part of the uvea. Cornea (C) and sclera (E) belong to the fibrous outer coat of the eyeball.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sarcoidosis develops granulomatous anterior uveitis. Which ocular finding is especially suggestive of granulomatous disease?",o:["Fine keratic precipitates","Hyphema","Subconjunctival hemorrhage","Busacca nodules","Papilledema"],a:3,e:"Busacca nodules are inflammatory nodules on the iris surface commonly associated with granulomatous uveitis such as sarcoidosis and tuberculosis.<br><br>Koeppe nodules occur at the pupillary margin and may occur in both granulomatous and nongranulomatous uveitis.<br><br>Subconjunctival hemorrhage (C) is unrelated to granulomatous inflammation. Hyphema (B) indicates bleeding rather than inflammatory nodules.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with posterior uveitis is most likely to complain of:",o:["Floaters and blurred vision","Severe itching","Purulent discharge","Colored halos only","Foreign body sensation"],a:0,e:"Posterior uveitis commonly affects vitreous and retina, producing floaters, blurred vision, and decreased visual acuity.<br><br>Pain and redness may be minimal compared with anterior uveitis.<br><br>Purulent discharge (C) suggests conjunctivitis. Itching (B) favors allergic disease. Foreign body sensation (E) is more typical of corneal pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The dilator pupillae muscle is supplied by:",o:["Parasympathetic fibers from oculomotor nerve","Sympathetic fibers","Trigeminal nerve","Trochlear nerve","Abducens nerve"],a:1,e:"The dilator pupillae muscle receives sympathetic innervation originating from the superior cervical ganglion.<br><br>Sympathetic interruption produces miosis as part of Horner syndrome.<br><br>Parasympathetic fibers from the oculomotor nerve (A) innervate the sphincter pupillae causing pupillary constriction. Trigeminal nerve (C) supplies facial sensation, not iris musculature.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 26-year-old female presents with sudden painful diminution of vision in one eye associated with impaired color vision and pain on eye movements. Fundus examination is initially normal. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Papilledema","Retinitis pigmentosa","Central retinal vein occlusion","Optic neuritis","Acute glaucoma"],a:3,e:"Optic neuritis is strongly associated with demyelinating disease, especially multiple sclerosis, and is among the highest-yield FCPS neuro-ophthalmology topics.<br><br>Patients classically present with unilateral painful visual loss, dyschromatopsia, central scotoma, and pain aggravated by eye movement. The optic disc may initially appear normal in retrobulbar neuritis.<br><br>Papilledema (A) is usually bilateral with preserved vision initially. Acute glaucoma (E) causes corneal edema and raised intraocular pressure. CRVO (C) produces retinal hemorrhages rather than painful visual loss with color desaturation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic nerve disease demonstrates an afferent pupillary defect during swinging flashlight test. What is this sign called?",o:["Argyll Robertson pupil","Marcus Gunn pupil","Adie tonic pupil","Horner pupil","Hutchinson pupil"],a:1,e:"Relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD) indicates asymmetric optic nerve or severe retinal disease and is classically detected by the swinging flashlight test.<br><br>The affected eye paradoxically dilates when illuminated because of reduced afferent input to the midbrain pupillary pathway.<br><br>Argyll Robertson pupil (A) accommodates but does not react. Horner syndrome (D) causes miosis and ptosis. Adie pupil (C) is tonic and poorly reactive but not an RAPD.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Bilateral optic disc swelling due to raised intracranial pressure is termed:",o:["Optic neuritis","Retrobulbar neuritis","Optic atrophy","Papilledema","Ischemic optic neuropathy"],a:3,e:"Papilledema is optic disc edema specifically caused by raised intracranial pressure and is usually bilateral. Early visual acuity may remain normal despite significant disc swelling.<br><br>Common symptoms include headache, vomiting, transient visual obscurations, and enlarged blind spot. Chronic papilledema eventually leads to secondary optic atrophy.<br><br>Optic neuritis (A) causes painful visual loss. Ischemic optic neuropathy (E) produces sudden disc edema with visual loss but is not caused by raised intracranial pressure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with pituitary macroadenoma most classically develops which visual field defect?",o:["Homonymous hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Central scotoma","Altitudinal defect","Bitemporal hemianopia"],a:4,e:"Pituitary tumors compress the optic chiasm where crossing nasal retinal fibers are located, producing bitemporal visual field loss.<br><br>Visual field testing is a repeatedly recalled neuro-ophthalmology topic in FCPS examinations.<br><br>Homonymous hemianopia (A) results from post-chiasmal lesions. Central scotoma (C) is common in optic neuritis. Ring scotoma (B) is associated with retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops pale optic disc with sharply defined margins following longstanding optic nerve damage. Which condition is this?",o:["Papilledema","Central retinal artery occlusion","Papillitis","Choroiditis","Primary optic atrophy"],a:4,e:"Primary optic atrophy produces chalky white optic disc pallor with sharply demarcated margins due to degeneration of optic nerve fibers without prior swelling.<br><br>Common causes include optic nerve compression, multiple sclerosis, and tabes dorsalis.<br><br>Papilledema (A) causes swollen hyperemic discs. Papillitis (C) is inflammatory optic disc swelling rather than established atrophy. CRAO (B) primarily affects retinal circulation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with sudden painless visual loss upon awakening. Fundus examination reveals swollen pale optic disc with splinter hemorrhages. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Optic neuritis","Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy","Papilledema","Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage"],a:1,e:"Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy (AION) results from impaired posterior ciliary artery circulation to the optic nerve head.<br><br>It commonly affects elderly hypertensive or diabetic patients and presents with sudden painless monocular visual loss and altitudinal field defects.<br><br>Optic neuritis (A) is usually painful and occurs in younger patients. Papilledema (C) is typically bilateral with preserved early vision. Retinal detachment (D) causes flashes and floaters.<br><br><em>(Recall and Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The optic nerve is embryologically derived from:",o:["Surface ectoderm","Mesoderm","Neuroectoderm","Endoderm","Neural crest only"],a:2,e:"The optic nerve develops from the optic stalk, which is derived from neuroectoderm. It is therefore considered a CNS tract rather than a peripheral nerve.<br><br>This explains why optic neuritis is associated with central demyelinating diseases such as multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Surface ectoderm (A) forms the lens. Neural crest (E) contributes to corneal stroma and endothelium but not the optic nerve itself.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic neuritis most commonly demonstrates which visual field defect?",o:["Bitemporal hemianopia","Homonymous hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Altitudinal defect","Central scotoma"],a:4,e:"Central scotoma is characteristic of papillomacular bundle involvement in optic neuritis and explains impaired central vision and color perception.<br><br>Red desaturation is another highly tested feature.<br><br>Altitudinal defects (D) are more characteristic of ischemic optic neuropathy. Bitemporal hemianopia (A) indicates chiasmal compression. Ring scotoma (C) is associated with retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with longstanding papilledema eventually develops optic disc pallor and visual deterioration. This stage is termed:",o:["Papillitis","Secondary optic atrophy","Retrobulbar neuritis","Toxic optic neuropathy","Choroiditis"],a:1,e:"Persistent optic disc edema eventually destroys optic nerve fibers leading to secondary optic atrophy characterized by pale discs with blurred margins.<br><br>Visual prognosis becomes poor once atrophy develops.<br><br>Primary optic atrophy differs by having sharply defined margins. Toxic optic neuropathy (D) causes bilateral central visual loss without preceding papilledema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The optic nerve passes through which structure to enter the cranial cavity?",o:["Superior orbital fissure","Cribriform plate","Inferior orbital fissure","Foramen rotundum","Optic canal"],a:4,e:"The optic nerve enters the cranial cavity through the optic canal accompanied by the ophthalmic artery.<br><br>Compression at this location by tumors or fractures may produce optic neuropathy.<br><br>The superior orbital fissure (A) transmits cranial nerves III, IV, VI, and V1 but not the optic nerve. Foramen rotundum (D) transmits V2.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with methanol poisoning most commonly develops damage to the:",o:["Cornea","Ciliary body","Lens capsule","Iris sphincter","Optic nerve"],a:4,e:"Methanol toxicity causes severe optic neuropathy leading to sudden visual loss, optic disc edema, and eventual optic atrophy.<br><br>Prompt treatment with fomepizole or ethanol and correction of acidosis is critical.<br><br>Corneal injury (A) is not the primary site of methanol toxicity. Lens capsule involvement (C) does not explain acute toxic blindness.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic nerve compression from meningioma develops gradual progressive visual loss. Which sign strongly suggests compressive optic neuropathy?",o:["Severe ocular pain","Corneal edema","Hypopyon","Keratic precipitates","Optociliary shunt vessels"],a:4,e:"Optociliary shunt vessels are collateral venous channels seen in chronic optic nerve compression, especially optic nerve sheath meningioma.<br><br>Progressive visual decline and optic atrophy are common associated findings.<br><br>Hypopyon (C) occurs in severe anterior uveitis. Keratic precipitates (D) indicate intraocular inflammation. Corneal edema (B) suggests endothelial dysfunction or glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which part of the visual pathway is affected in homonymous hemianopia?",o:["Retina only","Optic chiasm","Post-chiasmal pathway","Cornea","Lens"],a:2,e:"Homonymous hemianopia results from lesions posterior to the optic chiasm involving optic tract, optic radiations, or occipital cortex.<br><br>The visual field defect affects the same side in both eyes.<br><br>Chiasmal lesions (B) classically cause bitemporal hemianopia. Corneal (D) and lens (E) lesions do not produce neurological visual field defects.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic neuritis is at greatest long-term risk of developing:",o:["Cataract","Episcleritis","Retinal detachment","Acute glaucoma","Multiple sclerosis"],a:4,e:"Optic neuritis is strongly associated with demyelinating disease and may be the presenting manifestation of multiple sclerosis.<br><br>MRI brain lesions significantly increase future MS risk.<br><br>Cataract (A) and glaucoma (D) are unrelated degenerative disorders. Episcleritis (B) is superficial scleral inflammation and not linked strongly to demyelinating optic neuropathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal fibers cross at the optic chiasm?",o:["Temporal retinal fibers","Superior retinal fibers only","Macular fibers only","Inferior retinal fibers only","Nasal retinal fibers"],a:4,e:"Nasal retinal fibers decussate at the optic chiasm, while temporal retinal fibers remain uncrossed.<br><br>Compression of crossing nasal fibers by pituitary tumors produces bitemporal hemianopia.<br><br>Temporal fibers (A) remain ipsilateral. Superior and inferior fibers (D and E) are not the basis for chiasmal crossing patterns.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic atrophy is most likely to have:",o:["Hyperemic swollen disc","Hypopyon","Corneal ulcer","Hyphema","Pale optic disc"],a:4,e:"Optic atrophy represents degeneration of optic nerve fibers and appears clinically as optic disc pallor.<br><br>Visual acuity, color vision, and pupillary reactions are often impaired.<br><br>Hyperemic swollen disc (A) occurs in active disc edema rather than atrophy. Hyphema (D) and hypopyon (B) involve the anterior chamber rather than the optic nerve.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with giant cell arteritis develops sudden irreversible visual loss due to arteritic ischemic optic neuropathy. Which laboratory finding is classically elevated?",o:["Serum calcium","ESR","Bilirubin","Serum potassium","Creatinine kinase"],a:1,e:"Giant cell arteritis is an ophthalmic emergency because untreated disease may rapidly cause bilateral blindness. ESR and CRP are typically markedly elevated.<br><br>Immediate high-dose systemic corticosteroids should be started when suspected.<br><br>Serum calcium (A) and bilirubin (C) are not diagnostic markers of arteritic ischemic optic neuropathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic neuritis demonstrates reduced ability to identify red color. This symptom is called:",o:["Nyctalopia","Photopsia","Metamorphopsia","Diplopia","Dyschromatopsia"],a:4,e:"Color vision impairment, especially red desaturation, is an important early feature of optic neuritis and optic nerve dysfunction.<br><br>It may persist even after recovery of visual acuity.<br><br>Nyctalopia (A) indicates rod dysfunction as in retinitis pigmentosa. Metamorphopsia (C) occurs in macular disease. Photopsia (B) is typical of retinal traction or detachment.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which meningeal coverings surround the optic nerve?",o:["Pia only","Dura only","Dura, arachnoid, and pia","Arachnoid only","Pia and arachnoid only"],a:2,e:"The optic nerve is surrounded by all three meningeal layers because it is embryologically an extension of the CNS.<br><br>Raised intracranial pressure is transmitted along the subarachnoid space around the optic nerve, causing papilledema.<br><br>Dura alone (B) is incomplete. Pia and arachnoid without dura (E) do not represent full meningeal investment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with compressive optic neuropathy most commonly develops which pattern of visual loss?",o:["Sudden painful visual loss","Rapid bilateral blindness within minutes","Episodic halos around lights","Acute photophobia with hypopyon","Gradual progressive visual decline"],a:4,e:"Compressive optic neuropathy from tumors such as pituitary adenoma or meningioma usually causes slowly progressive visual loss with optic atrophy and field defects.<br><br>Early recognition is essential because prolonged compression may produce irreversible nerve fiber damage.<br><br>Sudden painful loss (A) suggests optic neuritis. Halos (C) suggest corneal edema or glaucoma. Hypopyon (D) indicates severe inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with pituitary macroadenoma complains of progressive difficulty seeing objects on both sides while walking. Perimetry demonstrates temporal field loss in both eyes. Which part of the visual pathway is compressed?",o:["Optic nerve","Optic chiasm","Optic tract","Lateral geniculate body","Occipital cortex"],a:1,e:"Pituitary adenomas classically compress the central portion of the optic chiasm where crossing nasal retinal fibers decussate, producing bitemporal hemianopia.<br><br>This is among the most frequently recalled neuro-ophthalmology MCQs in FCPS and JCAT examinations. Progressive peripheral field loss with preserved central vision is highly characteristic.<br><br>Optic nerve lesions (A) produce monocular visual loss. Optic tract lesions (C) cause contralateral homonymous hemianopia. Occipital cortex lesions (E) may produce homonymous defects with macular sparing.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A lesion involving the right optic nerve before the chiasm produces:",o:["Right monocular blindness","Left monocular blindness","Bitemporal hemianopia","Left homonymous hemianopia","Right homonymous hemianopia"],a:0,e:"Prechiasmal lesions affect fibers from only one eye, resulting in ipsilateral monocular visual loss.<br><br>Causes include optic neuritis, compressive optic neuropathy, ischemic optic neuropathy, and trauma.<br><br>Bitemporal hemianopia (C) localizes to the chiasm. Homonymous hemianopia (D and E) indicates post-chiasmal lesions.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Nasal retinal fibers cross in the:",o:["Optic nerve head","Lateral geniculate body","Optic radiation","Visual cortex","Optic chiasm"],a:4,e:"The optic chiasm contains decussating nasal retinal fibers responsible for carrying temporal visual field information.<br><br>Understanding fiber crossing is essential for localization of visual field defects in FCPS neuro-ophthalmology questions.<br><br>Optic radiations (C) and visual cortex (D) are post-chiasmal structures where fibers no longer cross.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with right optic tract lesion develops which visual field defect?",o:["Right monocular blindness","Left monocular blindness","Bitemporal hemianopia","Right homonymous hemianopia","Left homonymous hemianopia"],a:4,e:"Optic tract lesions produce contralateral homonymous hemianopia because fibers carrying information from the opposite visual field travel together after the chiasm.<br><br>Right optic tract lesions affect left visual fields from both eyes.<br><br>Monocular blindness (A and E) localizes anterior to the chiasm. Bitemporal hemianopia (C) localizes to the optic chiasm itself.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A lesion affecting Meyer's loop in the temporal lobe classically produces:",o:["Bitemporal hemianopia","Total blindness","Inferior quadrantanopia","Central scotoma","Superior quadrantanopia"],a:4,e:"Meyer's loop carries inferior retinal fibers representing the superior visual field. Temporal lobe lesions therefore produce contralateral superior quadrantanopia (\"pie in the sky\").<br><br>This is a classic localization question repeatedly asked in ophthalmology and neurology recalls.<br><br>Inferior quadrantanopia (C) results from parietal lobe involvement. Central scotoma (D) commonly occurs in optic neuritis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parietal lobe lesion develops which visual field defect?",o:["Superior quadrantanopia","Inferior quadrantanopia","Bitemporal hemianopia","Central scotoma","Monocular blindness"],a:1,e:"Parietal optic radiations carry superior retinal fibers representing the inferior visual field, so lesions produce contralateral inferior quadrantanopia (\"pie on the floor\").<br><br>Visual pathway localization using field defects is highly tested in FCPS neuro-ophthalmology.<br><br>Temporal lobe lesions (A) produce superior quadrantanopia. Monocular blindness (E) indicates optic nerve involvement.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The primary visual cortex is located in the:",o:["Temporal lobe","Frontal lobe","Occipital lobe","Parietal lobe","Midbrain"],a:2,e:"The primary visual cortex (area 17) lies around the calcarine fissure of the occipital lobe and receives impulses from the lateral geniculate body via optic radiations.<br><br>Occipital lesions often produce congruous homonymous visual field defects.<br><br>Frontal lobe (B) lesions primarily affect motor function. Temporal and parietal lobes (A and D) contain optic radiations rather than the primary visual cortex itself.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Macular sparing in homonymous hemianopia strongly suggests a lesion involving the:",o:["Optic nerve","Optic chiasm","Occipital cortex","Retina","Cornea"],a:2,e:"Occipital cortical lesions may spare central macular vision because of dual blood supply from posterior and middle cerebral arteries.<br><br>Macular sparing is therefore an important localization clue for cortical visual pathway lesions.<br><br>Optic nerve lesions (A) cause monocular visual loss rather than homonymous defects. Chiasmal lesions (B) produce bitemporal field loss.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal fibers remain uncrossed at the optic chiasm?",o:["Nasal fibers","Superior fibers only","Macular fibers only","Inferior fibers only","Temporal fibers"],a:4,e:"Temporal retinal fibers remain ipsilateral and do not cross at the optic chiasm.<br><br>This arrangement ensures that visual information from the same visual field reaches the contralateral occipital cortex.<br><br>Nasal fibers (A) are the fibers that decussate. Superior and inferior fibers (D and E) are not classified according to crossing patterns.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops complete bitemporal hemianopia. Which lesion location is most likely?",o:["Bilateral occipital cortex","Bilateral retinas","Right optic tract","Left optic nerve","Central optic chiasm"],a:4,e:"Central chiasmal compression damages decussating nasal retinal fibers carrying temporal visual field information from both eyes.<br><br>Pituitary adenoma is the classic cause. Craniopharyngioma is another important differential in FCPS recalls.<br><br>Optic tract lesions (C) cause homonymous hemianopia. Optic nerve lesions (D) produce monocular visual loss.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic radiation lesion develops homonymous hemianopia. Pupillary light reflexes remain normal because the reflex pathway bypasses the visual cortex. Which structure is bypassed?",o:["Retina","Optic nerve","Optic tract","Visual cortex","Midbrain"],a:3,e:"The pupillary light reflex pathway diverges before reaching the visual cortex and synapses in the pretectal nucleus of the midbrain. Therefore, cortical lesions may produce visual field defects without affecting pupillary responses.<br><br>Homonymous hemianopia with intact pupillary reflexes strongly favors post-geniculate lesions. Optic nerve lesions (B) produce RAPD, while midbrain lesions (E) impair the reflex pathway directly. Optic tract lesions (C) may mildly affect pupillary responses.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with left occipital lobe infarction develops:",o:["Left homonymous hemianopia","Central scotoma only","Bitemporal hemianopia","Left monocular blindness","Right homonymous hemianopia"],a:4,e:"Occipital cortex lesions produce contralateral homonymous field defects because visual fibers have already crossed at the optic chiasm.<br><br>Occipital lesions classically produce highly congruous defects and may demonstrate macular sparing. Monocular blindness (D) localizes anterior to the chiasm, while bitemporal hemianopia (C) indicates chiasmal compression. Central scotoma (B) is typical of optic neuritis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"The lateral geniculate body is located in the:",o:["Midbrain","Cerebellum","Pons","Medulla","Thalamus"],a:4,e:"The lateral geniculate body is the thalamic relay nucleus where optic tract fibers synapse before projecting via optic radiations to the occipital cortex.<br><br>This is a repeatedly tested anatomy recall in FCPS neuro-ophthalmology. The midbrain (A) contains pupillary reflex centers rather than the primary visual relay nucleus. Pons (C) and medulla (D) are not part of the main visual pathway relay system.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with pituitary adenoma first develops peripheral temporal field loss because the tumor compresses:",o:["Temporal retinal fibers","Superior retinal fibers only","Macular fibers only","Inferior retinal fibers only","Nasal retinal fibers"],a:4,e:"Crossing nasal retinal fibers occupy the central optic chiasm and carry temporal visual field information.<br><br>Compression by pituitary adenoma therefore produces bitemporal hemianopia beginning peripherally. Temporal retinal fibers (A) remain uncrossed. Superior and inferior fibers (D and E) are not the main anatomical basis of chiasmal syndromes.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A lesion involving the right temporal lobe optic radiations causes:",o:["Left superior quadrantanopia","Left inferior quadrantanopia","Right superior quadrantanopia","Bitemporal hemianopia","Left monocular blindness"],a:0,e:"Temporal lobe optic radiations (Meyer's loop) carry inferior retinal fibers representing the superior visual field.<br><br>Right temporal lobe lesions therefore cause left superior quadrantanopia (\"pie in the sky\"). Inferior quadrantanopia (B) localizes to parietal lobe lesions. Monocular blindness (E) indicates optic nerve pathology.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral occipital lobe infarction is blind but retains normal pupillary reflexes. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Optic neuritis","Retinal detachment","Papilledema","Central retinal artery occlusion","Cortical blindness"],a:4,e:"Cortical blindness occurs due to bilateral occipital cortex damage with preservation of anterior visual pathways and pupillary reflexes.<br><br>The optic nerves and reflex arcs remain intact. CRAO (D) produces retinal whitening and abnormal fundus findings, while optic neuritis (A) causes painful optic nerve dysfunction. Retinal detachment (B) causes flashes and curtain-like defects.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Fibers carrying information from the superior visual field travel mainly through the:",o:["Parietal lobe","Temporal lobe","Occipital pole only","Optic disc","Retina only"],a:1,e:"Superior visual field information originates from inferior retinal fibers that pass through Meyer's loop in the temporal lobe.<br><br>Temporal lobe lesions therefore produce superior quadrantic visual field defects. Parietal lobe lesions (A) affect inferior visual fields. Retinal lesions (E) do not produce characteristic neurological quadrantanopias.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with right parietal lobe infarction most likely develops:",o:["Left inferior quadrantanopia","Left superior quadrantanopia","Bitemporal hemianopia","Right monocular blindness","Central scotoma"],a:0,e:"Parietal optic radiations carry superior retinal fibers representing the inferior visual field.<br><br>Right parietal lesions therefore produce left inferior quadrantanopia (\"pie on the floor\"). Superior quadrantanopia (B) localizes to temporal lobe involvement. Monocular blindness (D) localizes anterior to the chiasm.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which artery primarily supplies the visual cortex?",o:["Middle cerebral artery","Basilar artery only","Ophthalmic artery","Anterior cerebral artery","Posterior cerebral artery"],a:4,e:"The occipital visual cortex is supplied mainly by the posterior cerebral artery.<br><br>Occipital infarctions therefore commonly produce homonymous hemianopia with possible macular sparing. The ophthalmic artery (C) supplies ocular structures rather than cortical centers. Middle cerebral artery (A) contributes partially to macular cortical representation only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A lesion compressing the optic chiasm from below is most commonly caused by:",o:["Pituitary adenoma","Temporal lobe tumor","Occipital infarction","Optic neuritis","Retinal detachment"],a:0,e:"Pituitary adenomas enlarge upward from the sella turcica and compress the inferior aspect of the optic chiasm.<br><br>This classically causes progressive bitemporal hemianopia. Temporal lobe tumors (B) produce quadrantanopia rather than chiasmal syndromes. Retinal detachment (E) causes flashes, floaters, and curtain-like visual loss rather than symmetrical temporal field defects.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A contact lens wearer presents with severe ocular pain, photophobia, ring-shaped stromal infiltrate, and pain disproportionate to clinical findings. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Fungal keratitis","Acute glaucoma","Viral conjunctivitis","Episcleritis","Acanthamoeba keratitis"],a:4,e:"Acanthamoeba keratitis is a classic high-yield FCPS contact lens complication. Severe pain out of proportion to slit lamp findings is the key clue.<br><br>Ring infiltrate formation occurs later and diagnosis is often delayed because the disease mimics herpetic or fungal keratitis. Corneal scraping and confocal microscopy aid diagnosis. Fungal keratitis (A) usually follows vegetative trauma and shows feathery margins. Viral conjunctivitis (C) causes follicles and watery discharge. Episcleritis (D) is superficial and relatively painless.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent acute anterior uveitis develops seclusio pupillae. This complication results from:",o:["Corneal endothelial failure","Optic nerve compression","Retinal detachment","Vitreous hemorrhage","360° posterior synechiae"],a:4,e:"Seclusio pupillae occurs when posterior synechiae involve the entire pupillary margin, obstructing aqueous flow from posterior to anterior chamber.<br><br>This may lead to iris bombe and secondary angle-closure glaucoma. Early cycloplegics are crucial preventive therapy in anterior uveitis. Retinal detachment (C) and vitreous hemorrhage (D) are posterior segment complications unrelated to pupillary block. Corneal endothelial failure (A) causes edema rather than synechial obstruction.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with sudden painless visual loss and cherry-red spot at the macula. Which associated systemic condition should always be urgently investigated?",o:["Ankylosing spondylitis","Migraine only","Myasthenia gravis","Hyperthyroidism","Carotid artery disease"],a:4,e:"Central retinal artery occlusion is commonly embolic and requires urgent cardiovascular evaluation including carotid Doppler and cardiac assessment.<br><br>CRAO is considered an ocular stroke and may precede cerebral ischemic events. Ankylosing spondylitis (A) is associated with anterior uveitis. Myasthenia gravis (C) affects ocular motility rather than retinal circulation. Hyperthyroidism (D) causes thyroid eye disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with mature cataract develops painful red eye with elevated intraocular pressure due to leakage of lens proteins through an intact capsule. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Phacomorphic glaucoma","Angle recession glaucoma","Pigmentary glaucoma","Neovascular glaucoma","Phacolytic glaucoma"],a:4,e:"Phacolytic glaucoma occurs in hypermature cataracts when lens proteins leak through the capsule and obstruct trabecular outflow.<br><br>Patients present with painful red eye, high IOP, and a mature cataract. Definitive management is cataract extraction after pressure control. Phacomorphic glaucoma (A) is caused by swollen lens-induced angle closure rather than protein leakage. Neovascular glaucoma (D) is associated with retinal ischemia.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular condition is most strongly associated with HLA-B27 positivity?",o:["Retinitis pigmentosa","Acute anterior uveitis","Central retinal vein occlusion","Cataract","Retinal detachment"],a:1,e:"HLA-B27 positivity is classically associated with recurrent acute nongranulomatous anterior uveitis.<br><br>Associated systemic diseases include ankylosing spondylitis, reactive arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, and inflammatory bowel disease. Retinal detachment (E) is associated with myopia and retinal tears. CRVO (C) is associated with vascular risk factors.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic neuritis most characteristically demonstrates:",o:["Purulent discharge","Peripheral retinal hemorrhages","Bitemporal hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Central scotoma"],a:4,e:"Central scotoma results from involvement of papillomacular fibers and is one of the most repeatedly recalled optic neuritis findings.<br><br>Pain on eye movement and dyschromatopsia are additional key clues. Bitemporal hemianopia (C) localizes to the optic chiasm. Ring scotoma (D) is typical of retinitis pigmentosa. Retinal hemorrhages (B) suggest vascular retinal disease.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing diabetes develops new vessels at the optic disc. Which treatment is classically indicated?",o:["Cycloplegics","Nd:YAG capsulotomy","Penetrating keratoplasty","Trabeculectomy","Pan-retinal photocoagulation"],a:4,e:"Pan-retinal photocoagulation remains a standard treatment for proliferative diabetic retinopathy by reducing retinal ischemia and VEGF production.<br><br>Timely treatment significantly reduces risk of vitreous hemorrhage and tractional retinal detachment. Cycloplegics (A) are used in uveitis. Trabeculectomy (D) is glaucoma surgery. Nd:YAG capsulotomy (B) treats posterior capsular opacification.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful red eye has circumcorneal congestion, small irregular pupil, and keratic precipitates. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Acute conjunctivitis","Optic atrophy","Episcleritis","Retinal detachment","Acute anterior uveitis"],a:4,e:"Circumcorneal congestion with cells, flare, keratic precipitates, and posterior synechiae strongly indicates anterior uveitis.<br><br>Photophobia and ciliary spasm pain are important clinical features. Conjunctivitis (A) causes discharge without keratic precipitates. Episcleritis (C) is superficial and usually painless. Retinal detachment (D) presents with flashes and floaters.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops bitemporal hemianopia. Which lesion location is most likely?",o:["Occipital cortex","Temporal retina only","Optic nerve","Retina","Optic chiasm"],a:4,e:"Bitemporal hemianopia is the hallmark of chiasmal compression, most commonly due to pituitary adenoma.<br><br>Crossing nasal retinal fibers carrying temporal field information are preferentially affected. Occipital cortex lesions (A) produce homonymous defects. Optic nerve lesions (C) cause monocular blindness rather than bilateral temporal field loss.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which corneal layer does NOT regenerate after injury?",o:["Epithelium","Conjunctival epithelium","Endothelium","Tear film","Bowman membrane"],a:4,e:"Bowman membrane does not regenerate after destruction and heals by scar formation.<br><br>This is clinically important in corneal trauma and ulceration because permanent scarring may impair transparency. Corneal epithelium (A) regenerates rapidly. Tear film (D) is continuously replenished. Conjunctival epithelium (B) also regenerates efficiently.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe hypertension develops flame-shaped retinal hemorrhages and papilledema. Which grade of hypertensive retinopathy is most likely?",o:["Grade 1","Grade 2","Grade 3","Grade 4","Grade 0"],a:3,e:"Grade 4 hypertensive retinopathy is characterized by papilledema in addition to hemorrhages, exudates, and arteriolar changes.<br><br>It indicates malignant hypertension and requires urgent systemic management. Grade 1 and 2 disease (A and B) mainly show vascular narrowing and AV nicking. Grade 3 lacks papilledema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which cataract is most strongly associated with prolonged corticosteroid therapy?",o:["Nuclear cataract","Lamellar cataract","Traumatic cataract","Morgagnian cataract","Posterior subcapsular cataract"],a:4,e:"Posterior subcapsular cataract is strongly associated with steroid use, diabetes, and radiation exposure.<br><br>Patients complain prominently of glare and difficulty reading despite relatively preserved distance acuity initially. Nuclear cataract (A) commonly produces myopic shift. Traumatic cataract (C) follows ocular injury. Lamellar cataract (B) is congenital.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with papilledema initially retains normal visual acuity because:",o:["Retina is unaffected initially","Macular fibers are spared early","Optic nerve is completely normal","Lens compensates for edema","Choroid bypasses the optic nerve"],a:1,e:"In papilledema, early swelling primarily affects peripheral optic nerve fibers while central macular fibers remain relatively preserved initially.<br><br>Visual acuity deteriorates later when chronic edema causes optic nerve fiber damage and secondary optic atrophy. The optic nerve is not normal (C); it is swollen due to raised intracranial pressure. Lens compensation (D) has no role.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with vernal keratoconjunctivitis most characteristically develops:",o:["Giant papillae","Retinal hemorrhages","Posterior synechiae","Cherry-red spot","Optic atrophy"],a:0,e:"Vernal keratoconjunctivitis is a chronic allergic disorder characterized by giant cobblestone papillae, intense itching, and ropy discharge.<br><br>Shield ulcers are important corneal complications. Posterior synechiae (C) occur in anterior uveitis. Cherry-red spot (D) occurs in CRAO. Optic atrophy (E) indicates optic nerve degeneration.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual field defect is classically produced by temporal lobe lesions involving Meyer's loop?",o:["Inferior quadrantanopia","Monocular blindness","Bitemporal hemianopia","Central scotoma","Superior quadrantanopia"],a:4,e:"Meyer's loop carries inferior retinal fibers representing the superior visual field. Temporal lobe lesions therefore produce superior quadrantanopia.<br><br>This is a classic \"pie in the sky\" defect frequently tested in neuro-ophthalmology recalls. Inferior quadrantanopia (A) localizes to parietal lobe lesions. Monocular blindness (B) indicates optic nerve disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with rheumatoid arthritis develops severe scleral pain and bluish scleral thinning. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Episcleritis","Viral conjunctivitis","Allergic conjunctivitis","Corneal abrasion","Necrotizing scleritis"],a:4,e:"Necrotizing scleritis is a destructive autoimmune inflammation strongly associated with rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br>It may lead to scleral melting, perforation, and permanent visual loss. Episcleritis (A) is mild and self-limiting. Allergic conjunctivitis (C) causes itching and papillary reaction rather than scleral destruction. Viral conjunctivitis (B) produces watery discharge and follicles.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which structure provides nutrition to the outer retina and photoreceptors?",o:["Central retinal artery","Lens capsule","Optic disc","Vitreous","Choroid"],a:4,e:"The choroid supplies oxygen and nutrients to the retinal pigment epithelium and photoreceptor layer through its rich vascular network.<br><br>Compromise of choroidal circulation significantly affects photoreceptor survival. Central retinal artery (A) mainly supplies the inner retina. Lens capsule (B) has no role in retinal nutrition. Vitreous (D) is avascular.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops RAPD during swinging flashlight test. Which structure is most likely affected?",o:["Corneal epithelium","Trabecular meshwork","Lens capsule","Ciliary body","Optic nerve"],a:4,e:"Relative afferent pupillary defect strongly indicates unilateral or asymmetric optic nerve dysfunction or severe retinal disease.<br><br>It is commonly seen in optic neuritis, ischemic optic neuropathy, and compressive optic neuropathy. Corneal disease (A) and lens pathology (C) do not produce RAPD because afferent visual pathways remain intact. Trabecular meshwork (B) regulates aqueous drainage only.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with retinal detachment most commonly complains initially of:",o:["Purulent discharge","Colored halos","Severe itching","Diplopia","Flashes and floaters"],a:4,e:"Retinal traction stimulates photoreceptors causing flashes (photopsia), while vitreous degeneration produces floaters.<br><br>Progression leads to curtain-like visual field loss. Early recognition and surgery are critical for visual prognosis. Purulent discharge (A) suggests conjunctivitis. Diplopia (D) indicates ocular motility disorders. Colored halos (B) are typical of corneal edema or glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic glaucoma eventually develops which optic nerve change?",o:["Hyperemic swollen disc","Optic disc cupping","Cherry-red spot","Giant papillae","Mutton-fat keratic precipitates"],a:1,e:"Progressive glaucomatous optic neuropathy causes excavation and cupping of the optic disc due to loss of retinal ganglion cell axons.<br><br>Increased cup-to-disc ratio is among the most important examination findings in glaucoma. Cherry-red spot (C) occurs in CRAO. Giant papillae (D) occur in vernal conjunctivitis. Mutton-fat keratic precipitates (E) are associated with granulomatous uveitis.<br><br><em>(Ramay's Review of FCPS Part 1 Ophthalmology)</em>"},
];